New test results for assessing the age of asylum seekers in Sweden
The latest results of Swedish asylum seekers tested for a new method of medical assessment of age show that more than 80 percent of those tested were evaluated as persons over the age of 18, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Forensic Medicine Agency (Rettsmedicinalverket) began to conduct tests earlier this year.
They were designed to make an assessment of the age in the asylum process more accurate, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the real age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
At the moment, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent of the tested (2002) were estimated as 18 or older people, and in another 25 cases, the Forensic Medicine Agency estimated that the test person is 18 years or older.
In the case of 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person is "probably less than 18."
Tests are carried out only in cases where the age of a person is in doubt.
According to Johan Geransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results correspond to the results for the past months.
"We don't see a big difference with statistics in the past months, the numbers are quite appropriate," he told the portal.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as over the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers have lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, the age of 18 years or more.
However, after considering the 581 published results, the newspaper "Svenska Dagbladet" found that in 243 cases people openly stated that 18 he was being executed this year.
The method of conducting a medical assessment of the age, consisting of making x-rays of wisdom and tomography of the knee joints and give them to the analysis of dentists and radiologists, also caused criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is the endocrinologist of the Karolinska Institute, Claude Marcus, part of whose work is to assess the biological maturity of people in order to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
I had reasons to think about it, and I don't think we should use the measurement methods that are being used now.
The biological age is determined very inaccurately.
"If we can't identify it with certainty, we shouldn't pretend we can," he told the newspaper.
However, Geranssen from the agency of forensic medicine spoke in favor of the accuracy of the tests: in general, we can say that the risk of mistake a child for an adult is small.
With the greatest risk we are faced when a person is soon 18, in this case he is about 10 percent.
