Italy is tightening the tone towards the ships of NGOs saving migrants.
Italy has warned the NGOs that own rescue ships in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue their work if they do not obey the new rules governing their activities.
"If the NGO does not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin Daily Stampa.
Minniti's warning came a day after Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization "Jugend Rettet," on suspicion that its crew was actually collaborating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which worked only a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed accusations brought against her by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartozio.
"For us, the salvation of human life is and will remain the highest priority, so we are very sorry that we can not continue activities in the search and rescue zone," the organization said in a statement.
"We will be able to assess all the charges now, only after we gather all the information and we can assess the situation."
The Italian authorities have been following the Juventa vessel, owned by the Jugend Rettet, since October.
His crew is suspected of taking on entire lifeboats on board migrants, whom traffickers sent directly to them, and allowed the smugglers to leave with boats that they could use again.
At least one such meeting is expected to take place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the charges, the contents of which were published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the orders of the Italian coast authorities, which control rescue operations in this zone, rather from humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct presupposes mainly that Juventa-type vessels will have on board an Italian police officer who will monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to submit to the code: "Save Children," the Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Spread Hugs from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that she considered the new rules unnecessary, but acceptable, provided they did not entail any "significant changes or interference" with rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is the Nobel Prize-winning organization "Doctors Without Borders" (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said that a sharp decline in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations in recent weeks indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coast guard and cooperation with local mayors are bearing fruit.
"In the last days, we have begun to see the light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
He announced plans for further negotiations with the Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
