Sentence of Michelle Carter for reports that prompted Conrad Roy's suicide
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for the fact that she with the help of text messages and phone calls prompted the suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20, will have to serve 15 months in prison and another five years of probation.
In June, Carter was found guilty of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at a hearing on Thursday: "My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free until the appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, squeezing his hands and lowering her eyes.
"With her actions, she killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her life.
She did not recognize responsibility," she said.
"She didn't show remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic case she regrets deeply about."
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her "age, level of maturity, or even mental illness did not affect her actions in a noticeable way."
The prosecutor read the statements of Roy's mother Lynn Roy, which says: "It has not been a single day before I mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I can handle it - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever.
Sister Roy Camdin Roy said that she is relentlessly haunted by the idea that she will never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"To deprive a person who has always been with me since I was born is a pain that will remain with me for the rest of his life," she said.
This case is likely to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would be responsible for a person's advice to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife don't know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before the suicide, she wrote, "You have to do it, Conrad" and "You only need to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said that Carter wanted to get attention through Roy's death, and forbade her from communicating with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of lawyers on this matter are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of the murder of her British apartment neighbor in Italy and was acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old Knox published her dissenting opinion in the Los Angeles Times, which claimed: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
