The Emergence of Similarity: The artist creates portraits with the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall at the Friedman Gallery in New York, people's faces hang from the ceiling on the wire - white, black and brown, all elusively similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg of brushstrokes and hair prunings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent pruning from Fort Levenworth prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous transfer of confidential diplomatic telegrams on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called "The Emergence of Resemblance."
This is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender and famous dissident who Barack Obama commuted the sentence just three days before the end of his presidency.
Analyzing the DNA computer program obtained from Manning and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of individuals that might have people with the genome, Dewey-Harborg created a deep, albeit difficult to perceive, manifesto not only on the plasticity of DNA data - different ways of interpreting them and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also the concept of identity.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward, but from adolescence openly said that she considers herself a woman, in 2013 was sentenced to 20 episodes, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in the prison were inaccessible, so only one photograph of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie, in which Manning in a platinum shade of a wig, clearly feeling embarrassing, sitting behind the wheel of the car; with this photo she was associated.
In 2015, Dewey Harborg completed her 2012 project "Vision of Strangers."
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people with the help of court evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this debris and creating images of what these people could look like.
And then she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article," she explained at a show off the show on the new press show.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted to get a portrait created from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her muse, who was in prison, became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters for two years.
They even wrote a book of comics "Suppressed Images," illustrated by Shoilie Kanungo, who portrayed how in the future the president would soften the punishment of Chelsea and she will be able to visit the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama really decided to release Manning just a few days after the book's release came out was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a Kansas military prison.
There is something profound and strong in the fact that the exhibition opens just now, when Donald Trump declares war on people who reveal secret information in the government, and invents new ways to incite on Twitter the enmity that he is called to soften.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of this in time, she said that "it's not accidental."
In a statement written on the galley's wall, Manning's huge signature below (with a heart instead of a point over the "i" in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic division based on sex, race, sexual orientation and culture."
On the opposite side is its mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar from pencil-prescribed by C, G and A.
Turning on 200 letters (or nucleotides, as a scientifically exquisitely expressed artist), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how we all are surprisingly similar, at least in its biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open genetic data is to interpret and how subjective it is," said Dea-Harborg; her 2007 video "False Memories" is also displayed here.
"DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of these stories are here."
The last part of the exposition, which can be found in one room, is the novel mentioned above in comics.
