For a man gripped by such a passion for old papers, get support from the National Fund and the English Academy of Sciences and the English Academy of History and live in the castle for four months ("Honestly, I've stayed there a little") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the "new" Victorian castle for all day, walked through the archives and considered numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that lay in the moat of the century.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talked to the foresters, gardeners and sometimes with artists who worked on illustrations to his book.
Then at night he "drinked his whisky and sat down to write."
The history of Scotney Castle is not very much studied because the National Foundation gained full access to it only in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived there ten years later, the staff was only beginning to deal with the archive, which he describes as "that aristocrats had been dumped in the attic for centuries."
The diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think that the land disputes are boring," says Rhodes, "but for this birch two families beating.
It's a good thing, guys!"
In some of the collection's stories, the castle becomes the starting point for wider research in English history: for example, in the "Educator," the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is information about the revolt that occurred in the castle in 1380, in a book called "Kenta and Sussex's Knight's Families," says Rhodes.
"The peasant revolt began in these places, and I thought that revolt was a good start.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other stories are strongly related to the history of the castle - for example, the "Priest," which tells about the Jesuit priest, whom the Darrel family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or the "Smuggler," about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrel, who is believed to have staged his own funeral, stuffing the coffin with stones (it was discovered a few years later, when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrels are the father of Rhodes's favorite family of all that Scotneys populated: "The gentlemen seem to have been a perfect scam, always in debt and spent money on what they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrel men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I imagine them as a company of cute guys who know how to care for the heirs of great fortunes.
After finishing the work at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to get a unique writing experience.
He lived two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elimyanymyaki - a place where at the beginning of the 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was overgrown with wood.
But Skotni remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like this: damn it, I have to go back to real life."
