Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help ease the VZK.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms in those who suffer from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the U.S. and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase the tolerance of the intestine.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the intestine are ensuring that harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells that can trigger the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severely disturbed towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in the intestine, there are cells that increase tolerance.
And this bacteria need tryptophan - one of the building elements of protein - to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophanes were kept in the diet of mice, the more these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same thing would work for humans: the combination of L. reuteri and a trythophane-rich diet may contribute to a more tolerant and less anti-inflammable environment in the intestine.
Postdoc, Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barangavas, studying the variety of immune cells increasing tolerant, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and the other group that belonged to the same line but was kept separately.
She suggested that the difference may be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mice's intestinal cells were sequenced and six species of bacteria present in mice with immune cells but missing from mice without them were found.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells, received L. reuteri, and they had immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then carried small portions of fluid - without bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the number of tryptopphan in the food of mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells also fell twice.
Dr. Cervantes-Barang explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptopphone from L. reuteri contribute to the development of cells in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found.
She says: "Perhaps the development of these cells should be strengthened, because these cells depend on the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines.
High levels of tryptopphan in the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to the expansion of their populations."
