The requisition for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to the records of the armed forces provided to the magazine, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine Helicopter to the South Lawn to an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as 240,000.
The white and green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the Marine One, when the president is on board, became the centerpiece of the July 17 event at the White House, which showcased American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and top White House officials surveyed technology from all fifty states.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was exhibited near a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the Helicopter Department responsible for the management of the helicopter, the White House Military Department ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or FRAGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of a "unusual event."
"I just wanted you to make sure that you know, because it's an unusual much-reaching event in the press," - wrote the commander of HMX-1 in an email to his boss, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter will arrive on the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and will remain there before the lawn is vacated between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to fly back in accordance with restrictions on working hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security guards remained near the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by the magazine TIME, it was unclear whether the second crew was required.
Hetcha's law prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event is inconsistent with this decree.
"We asked, among other things, whether this violation of Hatch's law, and we were told that no, "the commander wrote.
"It seems that you have nowhere to go," the deputy chief replied.
The event "Made in America" was declared the White House as an official event, and Hatch's law did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance the health care reform that was at the time in the development of the Senate and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft, known as the Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes, is unlikely to be a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But to ask them for the only advantage of photo opportunity is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with reports of complaints about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessor.
The White House is thrilled with the show "Made in America," which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," White House deputy spokeswoman Lindsay Walters said.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the United States president's transportation to the White House to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight made for the event "Made in America" was counted to the crew at the expense of the necessary training flights in a month.
The helicopters of the unit on that day also flew 11 additional hours as part of the "Nen-presidential tasks" support.
According to the White House, the taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter in the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep the budget on presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Ministry of Defense's 2017 fiscal year, the Department of Defense's reimbursement rate for VH-3D is $23,380 per hour.
The records of the unit recorded that the flight time in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield based on the marine aviation base of the Kuantico Marines in Virginia.
The White House says the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than that rate.
Calculating the cost for taxpayers, based on an approximate rate of reimbursement, is completely wrong, "says Walters.
These exemplary rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in annual appropriations.
According to a study conducted in 2015 by the RAND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and the costs indicated in the contract.
At the time, former White House spokesman Sean Spicer spoke in defense of the use of the helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to show things done in America this week," Spicer said.
And I know that the company and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are hundreds, if not thousands, of the people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, which has worked tirelessly for so many Americans.
Therefore, of course, it is quite appropriate to pay attention to this.
It was not clear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter, inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat on the driver's seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump appealed to representatives of the company, joking with the press on the company's own fleet of products.
"I know "Sikorsky," the president said. I have three of them.
